## .NET 8 Migration: BackgroundProcessor

### Critical Breaking Change

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8. `ThreadAbortException` is never raised. Your `Stop()` method will crash and your cleanup logic in the `catch` block will never execute.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _workerTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _workerTask = Task.Run(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass token so blocking calls become cancellable
                var item = await GetNextItemAsync(token);
                await ProcessItemAsync(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Replaces ThreadAbortException handling
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit loop cleanly — no ResetAbort needed
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        timeout ??= TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2);

        _cts.Cancel(); // signals cancellation — replaces _running = false + Abort

        if (_workerTask is not null)
        {
            // Wait with timeout instead of Thread.Sleep + Abort
            if (await Task.WhenAny(_workerTask, Task.Delay(timeout.Value)) != _workerTask)
            {
                // Worker didn't finish in time — log warning, but no force-kill.
                // .NET 8 has no safe equivalent to Thread.Abort().
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }
}
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---|---|
| **`Thread.Abort()` → `PlatformNotSupportedException`** | No equivalent exists. Use `CancellationToken` for cooperative cancellation. |
| **`ThreadAbortException` never thrown** | Replace with `OperationCanceledException`. The `when` guard avoids catching unrelated exceptions. |
| **`Thread.ResetAbort()` removed** | Unnecessary — `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow. Just `break`. |
| **Blocking `GetNextItem()` ignores cancellation** | If it blocks on a `BlockingCollection`, use `.Take(token)`. If it's I/O, make it async and pass `token`. Without this, `Stop` hangs. |
| **`volatile bool` flag** | Works but is a weaker pattern. `CancellationToken` is checked by the entire BCL (streams, HTTP, EF, channels, etc.). |
| **`Thread.Sleep` for shutdown** | Replaced by `Task.WhenAny` with timeout — non-blocking and deterministic. |
| **No `IDisposable`** | `CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed. |

### If you can't make GetNextItem async

Use `BlockingCollection<T>` with token support or wrap the synchronous call:

```csharp
// Option: run sync blocking call on a thread pool thread with cancellation
var item = await Task.Run(() => GetNextItem(token), token);
```

### Minimal sync-only version (if async isn't feasible)

```csharp
public void Stop()
{
    _cts.Cancel();
    // Cooperative: worker checks token.IsCancellationRequested
    _workerThread?.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2));
    // If still alive, you can only log — there's no safe force-kill
}
```

**Bottom line:** .NET 8 has no forced thread termination. Every blocking call in your loop must accept a `CancellationToken` or your `Stop` will hang. Audit `GetNextItem` and `ProcessItem` first — that's where the real migration work is.
